amework. Such issues as the Passion of Christ, penitential suffering, suffering and gender, the fate of unbaptized children, and the pain and suffering of souls and resurrected bodies in hell are all considered, to demonstrate how the masters established a clear and precise consensus for their explanations of the human condition. DONALD MOWBRAY gained his PhD from the University of Bristol.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPainxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesy13th century. 0aPainxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrines, 13th century. 0aSufferingxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesy13th century. 0aSufferingxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrines, 13th century. 0aTheologyxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aTheologyxHistory, Middle Ages, 600-1500. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aFourteenth Century.  aGender.  aHell.  aHuman Pain.  aMedieval Theology.  aPassion of Christ.  aPenitential Suffering.  aSuffering.  aThirteenth Century.  aUniversity of Paris.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846157516?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846157516423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846157516/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles